      "\n   - Base case `[]`: `count x [] = 0` and both other counts are zero.\n   - Inductive step: consider `y :: l`.\n      - If `x = y`, then `(y :: l).count x = 1 + l.count x`, `(y :: l).filter (· ≤ a)` is `if y ≤ a then y :: (l.filter (· ≤ a)) else (l.filter (· ≤ a))`, etc.\n      - So the count of `x` in the filter is `if y ≤ a then 1 + (l.filter (· ≤ a)).count x else (l.filter (· ≤ a)).count x`.\n      - Similarly for `a < y`.\n      - Now, in the sum, we have:\n         - `(y :: l).count x = 1 + l.count x`.\n         - `(filter (· ≤ a) (y :: l)).count x + (filter (a < ·) (y :: l)).count x = (if y ≤ a then 1 else 0) + ...`. \n\n   But a better approach might be:\n   For any list, the count in the original is the count in the smaller plus larger parts because every element is partitioned into exactly one of the two parts, and count is additive.\n\n   Alternatively, perhaps there's a simpler proof based on `count` being the sum of booleans:\n   - `(l.count x)` is the sum over `y ∈ l` of `if y = x then 1 else 0`.\n   - `(smaller a l).count x` is the sum over `y ∈ l` with `y ≤ a` of `if y = x then 1 else 0`.\n   - `(larger a l).count x` is the sum over `y ∈ l` with `y > a` of `if y = x then 1 else 0`.\n   - So, their sum is the sum over all `y ∈ l` of `if y = x then 1 else 0` because any `y` is either `≤ a` or `> a`.\n\n   This seems straightforward in math, but perhaps less so in Lean. \n\n   Alternatively, perhaps we can find a lemma in Lean that already does this, but I'm not sure.\n\n   But perhaps the following will work in Lean:",
