      "\n  - `x` is in `smaller` is `x ≤ x`, true.\n  - Actually, no: `smaller` is `(x :: rest).filter (y ≤ x) = x :: (rest.filter (y ≤ x))`.\n  So `(smaller).count x = 1 + (rest.filter (y ≤ x)).count x`. \n  And `(rest.filter (y ≤ x)).count x = (rest.filter (y ≤ x)).count x ≤ rest.count x`.\n\nSimilarly, `larger = (x :: rest).filter (y > x) = rest.filter (y > x)` because `x ≯ x`.\nThus, `(larger).count x = 0`.\n\nHmm, but `l.count x = (x :: rest).count x = 1 + rest.count x`.\n\nBut then, `smaller.count x + larger.count x = (x :: (rest.filter (≤ x))).count x + 0 = 1 + (rest.filter (≤ x)).count x`, but `(rest.filter (≤ x)).count x = (rest.filter (≤ x)).count x ≤ rest.count x`, but we need it to be equal. \n\nWait no, because if you filter `≤ x`, then you keep `x`s, but not others. \n\nLet me do an example. Take `l = [x, x, y]`, where `x < y`. Then `smaller = [x, x, y].filter (≤ x) = [x, x]`, and `larger = [y]`.\nThen `smaller.count x = 2`, `larger.count x = 0`, and `l.count x = 2`. \n\nBut in the previous case, `smaller.count x + larger.count x = 2 + 0 = 2 = l.count x`, as desired. \n\nBut in `count_sum_above_below_pivot`, you are saying `(x :: x :: y :: []).count x = 2`, but `(smaller).count x = 2` and `(larger).count x = 0`, so `2 + 0 = 2`, which works.\n\nAnother example: `l = [x, y, x]`, `x < y`.\nThen `smaller = [x, x]`, `larger = [y]`, same as above.\n\nAnother example: `l = [x, x, x]`, then `smaller = [x, x, x]`, `larger = []`.\n`smaller.count x = 3`, `larger.count x = 0`, `l.count x = 3`.\n\nWait but in the `count_sum_above_below_pivot` lemma, for `l = [x, x, x]`, `smaller x l = l`, `larger x l = []`, then `l.count x = 3`, `smaller.count x + larger.count x = 3 + 0 = 3`.\n\nThe only tricky case is when `l = [x, y]` with `y < x`. \n\nIf `l = [x, y]`, `y < x`, then:\n`smaller = [y]`, `larger = []`.\n`l.count y = 1`, `smaller.count y = 1`, `larger.count y = 0`. OK.\n\nBut `l.count x = 1`, `smaller.count x = 0`, `larger.count x = 0`. \n\nBut the lemma says `l.coun